I’m so new to this that I’m still confounded at how the emotions come rushing forth at the end of some of these practices. Yoga is healing something deep within me…a part of me that is ashamed of myself, doesn’t love me, and feels like a clumsy failure. But I am also so gripped with the love and compassion for myself that is slowly making its way to the surface. I find myself in tears, telling myself, “It’s okay. This is new. You showed up for yourself. You’re worthy. I love you.” So while I may be frustrated at how hard this can be for me at times, I’m also proud of myself and the way I’m persisting. See you tomorrow.

I love your videos. Every year for the past 3 years, I have joined you and others for the 30 Days of Yoga. This year was especially special because in July, I had a foot that was in need of healing. It went on for several months. I wasn't able to do yoga. It finally came down to surgery and the week I was to set the surgery date, I found out I was pregnant. My little bud pushed me to heal and I was able to do yoga again without surgery. My baby saved me from surgery and your videos helped me get through to heal. I began this year doing Move. We were due to find out our baby's gender this past Tuesday but what they found was our little bud no longer had a heartbeat. I am still in the process of miscarriage and I haven't been able to find much comfort. I decided to try to get back in on Move. This practice moved my heart so. Thank you for helping people through so much. I don't think you know the impact you have on others but what you have done for me this past year, I can't ever repay.

That was a great practice, many thanks again Adriene. 👍 You have a gift of being able to make people feel completely at ease and with no judgement. Adrienne gets into crow differently than I am used to, and I think it doesnt work for my body type (or I'm just not used to it). But for anyone with wide hip placement, I think it's easier if you start from a wide legged squat, with toes touching the edge of the mat, before lifting off. Hands are probably placed a little wider as well. Just make sure that your weight is still being supported by the inner part of you hand. Good luck, all! 🥳

I thought it would be wise to start doing yoga again since I just picked up roller skating about a week ago. Oooh man, I am sore today so my crow sat in the nest, these thighs are on fire. Yoga and skating work together so effortlessly, all about core, balance and setting your mind free. All of 2020-2021 I was deep in depression and didn’t exercise or even leave my couch much. Nearly 2 weeks into this practice and today I just cried for the first time after doing yoga, I just feel so at peace, even though my entire body aches so badly!

I’ve taken on a lot of challenges in this journey so far, but this is the first day I’ve had to stop what I was doing, put my head on the mat, and try and find the strength to go on. 

I’m in the painstaking process of “leaving the nest” after college— after weeks of flubbed job interviews and rejected apartment applications, I’m feeling beaten down and defeated. All I want to do is spread my wings and soar out of here, so something about fighting to breathe in these poses until I collapsed, struggling to even prop myself back up with no hope of lifting off the ground had me feeling ready to slam the laptop closed and just give up for the first time in any yoga session.

I stayed with it, and I’ll be back tomorrow too. Giving up on my body and my future is not an option. I know I’m worthy and someday soon, I’ll take off and start my life for real. For the amount of patience and strength it's taking to get there, it must be something pretty good.

Move really feels much more challenging than Breath, or other monthly YWA calendars. Last year I began practicing with YWA in January and kept with it every day through April, then started to mix up YWA with other fitness and yoga activities. For all of 2021, I regularly practiced yoga at home several days a week. I am finding Move to be tough going, especially this week. It's discouraging to not be able to get my knees in my armpits at all, or quickly move in and out of the balancing poses, or do all the mountain climbers, etc. Obviously, a lot of this is on me, because only I can let go of my perfectionism. But I am grateful that I am not coming to a regular home practice for the first time this year, because I might have thought it wasn't for people like me (i.e., older, heavier, less flexible, with less strength). I know I made a lot of progress last year in my flexibility and strength so I am going to stick with it. This comment is really here for newbies who might be feeling bad that they can't do all of this. You're not imagining it. This is hard. But just do what you can do, keep trying, and you will get something from it. <3
